Title : Google Playstore App Rating prediction using best Model¶

Introduction¶

In predicting the rating of Apps in playstore there are many criterias which we have go through inorder to predict the best model for this data. Our dataset consists of some of the main criterias that are valid for the prediction of rating. Our dataset includes following variables that are taken in to consideration, Apps, Category, Reviws, Size, Installs, Type, Price, Content Rating , LastUpdated ,Genres, Current version, Android version.

In [13]:
data_train['Size'] = data_train['Size'].apply(lambda x : str(x).replace('M',''))
data_train['Size'] = data_train['Size'].apply(lambda x : str(x).replace('+',''))
data_train['Size'] = data_train['Size'].apply(lambda x : str(x).replace(',',''))
data_train['Size'] = data_train['Size'].apply(lambda x : str(x).replace('Varies with device','nan'))
data_train['Size'] = data_train['Size'].apply(lambda x :float(str(x).replace('k',''))/1000 if 'k' in str(x) else x)
data_train['Size']= data_train['Size'].astype(float)
data_train.dropna(subset=['Size'],inplace =True)

In [33]:
q1, q3 = np.percentile(non_zero_prices, [25, 75])
iqr = q3 - q1
lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * iqr

outliers = non_zero_prices[(non_zero_prices < lower_bound) | (non_zero_prices > upper_bound)]
ind =  non_zero_prices[(non_zero_prices > upper_bound) | (non_zero_prices < lower_bound)].index
non_zero_prices=non_zero_prices.drop(ind)
In [34]:

Lasso Regression¶

In [143]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso
alphas = np.logspace(-4, 2, 50)
cv_scores = []
for alpha in alphas:
    lasso = Lasso(alpha=alpha)
    scores = cross_val_score(lasso, x_train, y_train, cv=10, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
    cv_scores.append(-1 * np.mean(scores))
optimal_alpha = alphas[np.argmin(cv_scores)]
print("Optimal alpha value:", optimal_alpha)

Optimal alpha value: 0.0016768329368110084
